Product Description

Prefect Ethernet Expansion for Notebook

Ugreen USB 3.0 gigabit 10/100/1000Mbps ethernet network adapter enables you to add a network interface to your computer via USB. You could replace a broken internal network card, add a separately routable network interface, and transferring files peer-to-peer over Ethernet. Simply insert the adapter into a USB 3.0 port on your computer and begin to transfer large video, audio, and graphics files between your workstation and the network.

Faster and More Stable Network

Full 10/100/1000Mbps gigabit ethernet performance makes this USB to Ethernet Adapter faster and more reliable than most wireless connections.

You can enjoy your game and movies more smoothly. No More Waiting!

Sleek Aluminum Ethernet Adapter

The aluminum unibody case makes this USB RJ45 adapter stylish and good matcher for macbook. The aluminum network adapter is also anti-fingerprint and anti-corrosion.

Read more

Specification

1. USB3.0 to RJ45 adapter supports Gigabit networking over USB 3.0 with up to 5Gbps

2. Supports suspend mode and remote wakeup via link-up, magic packet, or external pin, USB-Powered

3. Compatible with Nintendo Switch, Nintendo Switch Lite, Windows 10/XP/Vista/7/8, Mac 10.6/10.7/10.8/10.9/10.10/10.11/10.12, Linux kernel 2.6 and later

Important Notes

1. Plug and Play only for Chrome OS, Windows 10/8.1/8

2. Driver needed for Windows7/XP/Vista, Mac OS, and Linux systems

3. Reboot your PC after driver installation, then connect this USB ethernet adapter to your computer and ethernet

4. Not supported on ARM-based Windows, including Surface RT and Surface 2

5. Mac System: System Preference--Network--Add a new network connection

6. Windows 7:Device Manager--USB-AX88179

7. This adapter does not support Wii u.

USB 3.0 supports 10/100 / 1000Mbps speed. Compatible with both USB2.0 and USB1.1

LED indicator

The LED indicator informs you of the working status

Aluminum shell design

The aluminum shell design is beautiful and stylish, but also anti-fingerprint and anti-corrosion.

      Question:
      Does it work with xbox? my ethernet port in my xbox one x broke
      Answer:
      This device is primarily intended to "replace" the internal Ethernet adapter located on the motherboard inside a PC. It may or may not work on any particular device other than a standard personal PC capable of running MS Windows. To answer your question one would need to know what kind of connection you are trying to… see more This device is primarily intended to "replace" the internal Ethernet adapter located on the motherboard inside a PC. It may or may not work on any particular device other than a standard personal PC capable of running MS Windows. To answer your question one would need to know what kind of connection you are trying to make to your Xbox. For example, are you trying to connect the Ethernet port on your computer to the Xbox? Or are you simply trying to connect your Internet modem directly to the xBox?

      If you are simply trying to fire up your xBox with an Internet connection, this raises another question: Why can't you simply use an Ethernet cable to directly connect your Xbox to your Internet modem? Is there some reason to suspect that your xBox has lost its capability to connect to the Internet? If so, there is a good chance the UGREEN USB Ethernet Adapter might not work for this because your xBox will only be compatible with the UGREEN USB Adapter if the xBox has a motherboard that appears to anything you connect to it EXACTLY as a PC computer running MS Windows.

      Your best way to figure this out is to contact tech support for your xBox and/or tech support at UGREEN and ask them if the xBox is, in fact, a fully PC-compatible "Windows" computer designed for a special purpose (gaming). If so, you may be in luck. But my gut feeling is that your xBox is NOT a kind of PC computer, but is one of many types of computer-like devices that can connect to the Internet such as "smart" phones, or TV streaming devices such as a Roku.

      FWIW - I have no reason whatsoever to believe that the UGREEN USB has been designed to work with smart phones, TV streaming devices, or ANYTHING that is not a "Windows PC computer". But I could be wrong, which is why I recommend you call one of the tech support services I recommended at the start of this response to your question.

      Which brings us back to your specific question: Why to you need to connect a UGREEN USB Ethernet modem to your xbox? Is it because your xbox is getting old and no longer works when you try to connect it to the Internet? If that is the case, the only thing that will work for you is to buy a new xBox or similar stand-alone gaming device.

      B. Young
      5.0 out of 5 stars Works with Nintendo Switch
      Reviewed in the United States on May 6, 2019
      Verified Purchase
      1. Build quality appears to be solid.

      2. The cord length is perfect for the Nintendo Switch dock. If you plug it into the back of the dock, there's a little over 1" of cord hanging out the back of the dock with the case closed, and then you have the Ethernet plug at the end of that.

      3. The color matches the standard gray Joy-Cons pretty well; it's a little bit darker, it's a shiny, metallic matte. The description and pictures on Amazon make it sound like it's a standard bright aluminum, but it's actually a dark matte gray. The box says "Aluminum Space Gray," and it is almost identical to the space gray-colored MacBooks and iPhones.

      I was previously connecting my Switch over 5 GHz 802.11ac Wi-Fi to a Netgear Nighthawk router w/custom firmware located about 6 ft away (basically the best case you could hope for connecting a Switch over Wi-Fi). I did a couple speed tests on the console to compare the wireless vs. the new wired connections.

      Wireless:
      23.5 Mbps download
      4.5 Mbps upload

      Wired:
      27.5 Mbps download
      4.5 Mbps upload

      My home internet speed is also 75 Mbps down/10 Mbps up, so the above speeds reflect the limits of the Nintendo Switch.

      5.0 out of 5 stars Works great with Nintendo Switch
      Reviewed in the United States on September 23, 2019
      Verified Purchase
      Bought this specifically for use with the Nintendo Switch, though it can be used for many other applications as well. So my review is mainly about this adapter in conjunction with the Switch. Was going to get the other UGREEN USB 3.0 gigabit model but saw this was the newest version, so went with this one.

      So far, it’s been great. Worked immediately with a docked Switch. It has enough length to plug into the USB 3.0 port in the back of the dock next to where you plug the HDMI cable and power cable and still close the door to keep it looking clean. (It’s well known that for some reason or another, Nintendo has this rear USB port set as 2.0, even though it is 3.0 capable.) So, if anything, getting any USB 3.0 adapter is just future proofing for whenever/if they change the back port. Regardless, this adapter will work in whichever USB port you plug it into.

      Another relatively known thing is that all LAN adapters apparently keep the Switch’s networking active, even in Sleep Mode. From what I have read this just keeps the Switch constantly warm or even hot, so unplugging either the adapter from the USB port, or the ethernet cable from the adapter(easier) after use is suggested by most. I have not tested to see if this adapter is an exception to that.

      If it helps, because of the constant plugging/unplugging with the Switch, I can say the ethernet port is smooth. Not so tight that it is a struggle to remove the ethernet cable, but that may vary between different cables so YMMV.

      Fit and finish is solid. Seems very durable, as unlike the older model, this has a metal casing and definitely seems like it can take some abuse.

      Been using consistently for about 2 weeks and seems a great product for the price and my use case. Will update if anything changes, but can definitely recommend this adapter for use with the Switch!

      5.0 out of 5 stars Ok, but enable Catalina driver from UGREEN website, under security & privacy settings...
      Reviewed in the United States on May 9, 2020
      Verified Purchase
      Confirm it DOES work on Mac Catalina (10.15.4), BUT not right out of the box... essential step missing (at least for me…) from installation guide and NOT intuitive...

      1. Per .pdf guide downloaded with correct driver on the UGREEN website for P/N "50922", download and install macOS driver for ASIX AX88179 device, granting installation permission on the 'general' tab in 'system preferences' -> 'security & privacy', by unlocking padlock, etc.

      2. Also per guide, re-boot, plug in adapter, and confirm driver loaded under 'about this Mac' -> 'overview' -> 'system report' -> 'hardware' -> 'USB',. It should indicate that "AX88179" is running under "USB 3.0 Bus".

      3. Next, (and NOT in the guide…) grant permission to the DRIVER ITSELF! Right after you boot-up, on the 'general' tab, under 'security & privacy', discretely, at the bottom of the pane it says, "Some systems software was blocked from loading." Unlock the padlock and, using the 'allow' button, select to enable "ASIX ELECTRONICS CORPORATION" from the list.

      4. Once permission is granted to the driver, access 'system preferences' -> 'network' and there should be an entry for "AX8817 Internet". Access should now work without adding anything further. (There may be instances where you have to create your own new service entry, by selecting the "AX8817…" interface, as per the guide).

      5. To note, no lights will show on the dongle/adapter until you plug in an active network cable. When lights at the end of the adapter are flashing, temporarily turn off WIFI and check access to the wired Internet. (I had trouble with my VPN reserving certain DNS servers, via WIFI, so had to renew DHCP and double-check the DNS servers before full wired ethernet access to the Internet.)

      Bottom line, UGREEN USB 3.0 / Ethernet adapter works well on 2015 MacBook Air running Catalina, but built-in OS device security/permission 'attributes' FOR THE DRIVER need to be manually unlocked/overcome to work correctly.

      By red-renard on May 9, 2020
      Confirm it DOES work on Mac Catalina (10.15.4), BUT not right out of the box... essential step missing (at least for me…) from installation guide and NOT intuitive...

      1. Per .pdf guide downloaded with correct driver on the UGREEN website for P/N "50922", download and install macOS driver for ASIX AX88179 device, granting installation permission on the 'general' tab in 'system preferences' -> 'security & privacy', by unlocking padlock, etc.

      2. Also per guide, re-boot, plug in adapter, and confirm driver loaded under 'about this Mac' -> 'overview' -> 'system report' -> 'hardware' -> 'USB',. It should indicate that "AX88179" is running under "USB 3.0 Bus".

      3. Next, (and NOT in the guide…) grant permission to the DRIVER ITSELF! Right after you boot-up, on the 'general' tab, under 'security & privacy', discretely, at the bottom of the pane it says, "Some systems software was blocked from loading." Unlock the padlock and, using the 'allow' button, select to enable "ASIX ELECTRONICS CORPORATION" from the list.

      4. Once permission is granted to the driver, access 'system preferences' -> 'network' and there should be an entry for "AX8817 Internet". Access should now work without adding anything further. (There may be instances where you have to create your own new service entry, by selecting the "AX8817…" interface, as per the guide).

      5. To note, no lights will show on the dongle/adapter until you plug in an active network cable. When lights at the end of the adapter are flashing, temporarily turn off WIFI and check access to the wired Internet.
